s]]\n", "name_user": "FilipinoMovies", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020:ever since the beginning it was already marketed that viva films is only distributor but not producer.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_films_produced_and_released_by_Viva_Films"}
{"title_page": "Our Town (1940 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1940 film by Sam Wood}}\n{{noplot|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Our Town\n| image          = Original movie poster for the film Our Town (1940 film).jpg\n| producer       = [[Sol Lesser]]\n| director       = [[Sam Wood]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Our Town]]'' {{small|(1938 play)}}|[[Thornton Wilder]]}}\n| screenplay     = [[Harry Chandlee]]<br>[[Frank Craven]]<br>Thornton Wilder\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Martha Scott]]<br>[[Fay Bainter]]\n| music          = [[Aaron Copland]]\n| cinematography = [[Bert Glennon]]\n| editing        = Sherman Todd\n| studio         = Sol Lesser Productions \n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1940|05|24|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Our Town''''' is a 1940 American [[drama (genre)|drama]] [[romance film]] adaptation of a [[Our Town|play of the same name]] by [[Thornton Wilder]] starring  [[Martha Scott]] as Emily Webb, and [[William Holden]] as George Gibbs.  The cast also included [[Fay Bainter]], [[Beulah Bondi]], [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]], [[Guy Kibbee]]  and [[Frank Craven]].  It was adapted by [[Harry Chandlee]], Craven and Wilder, and directed by [[Sam Wood]].\n\nThe film was a faithful reproduction of the play except for two significant changes: the film used scenery, whereas the play had not; the events of the third act, which in the play revolve around the death of one of the main characters, were turned into a dream from which she awakens, allowing her to resume a normal life. Producer [[Sol Lesser]] worked with Wilder in creating these changes.\n\nA radio adaptation of the film on ''[[Lux Radio Theater]]'' on May 6, 1940, used the altered film ending.\n\nThe U.S. copyright of the film was not renewed after its first term expired in 1968. However, because it is a [[derivative work]] from a play that is still under U.S. copyright, it is not deemed to be in the [[public domain]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=24em}}\n* [[William Holden]] - George Gibbs\n* [[Martha Scott]] - Emily Webb\n* [[Fay Bainter]] - Mrs. Julia Gibbs\n* Dix Davis - Joe Crowell Jr.\n* [[Beulah Bondi]] - Mrs. Myrtle Webb\n* [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]] - Dr. Frank F. Gibbs\n* [[Guy Kibbee]] - Mr. Charles Webb\n* Tim Davis - Si Crowell\n* [[Stuart Erwin]] - Howie Newsome\n* [[Frank Craven]] - Stage Manager\n* [[Doro Merande]] - Mrs. Louella Soames\n* Philip Wood - Simon Stimson\n* Ruth Tobey - Rebecca Gibbs (as Ruth Toby)\n* Douglas Gardiner - Wally Webb\n* Arthur B. Allen - Prof. Willard (as Arthur Allen)\n* [[Charles Trowbridge]] - Rev. Dr. Ferguson\n* [[Spencer Charters]] - Const. Bill Warren\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Score==\n[[Aaron Copland]] accepted the invitation to compose the musical score for the screen version of life in the small town of Grover's Corners, New Hampshire. He explained, \"For the film version, they were counting on the music to translate the transcendental aspects of the story. I tried for clean and clear sounds and in general used straight-forward harmonies and rhythms that would project the serenity and sense of security of the story.\" Copland arranged about ten minutes from the film score for a suite. It is dedicated to [[Leonard Bernstein]].<ref name=\"Boosey & Hawkes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boosey.com/cr/music/Aaron-Copland-Our-Town/2258 |title=Copland, Aaron Our Town (1940) Music from the film score |accessdate=2018-11-19|work=Boosey.com}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/36778/Our-Town/details |title=NY Times: Our Town |accessdate=2008-12-13|work=NY Times}}</ref>  Scott, who reprised her stage role as Emily Webb, was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. [[Aaron Copland]] was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]] and [[Thomas T. Moulton]] was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound]].<ref name=\"Oscars1941\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1941 |title=The 13th Academy Awards (1941) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-08-13|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title | id=0032881 | title=Our Town}}\n* {{amg movie|36778}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=85941}}\n* {{AFI film|id=4334|title=Our Town}}\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Our_Town|name=Our Town}}\n\n{{Sam Wood}}\n{{Thornton Wilder}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Our Town (1940 Film)}}\n[[Category:1940 films]]\n[[Category:1940s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sam Wood]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Sol Lesser]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Aaron Copland]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1901]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1904]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1913]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\nhttps://variety.com/1939/film/reviews/our-town-1200413018/\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1940 film by Sam Wood}}\n{{noplot|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Our Town\n| image          = Original movie poster for the film Our Town (1940 film).jpg\n| producer       = [[Sol Lesser]]\n| director       = [[Sam Wood]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Our Town]]'' {{small|(1938 play)}}|[[Thornton Wilder]]}}\n| screenplay     = [[Harry Chandlee]]<br>[[Frank Craven]]<br>Thornton Wilder\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Martha Scott]]<br>[[Fay Bainter]]\n| music          = [[Aaron Copland]]\n| cinematography = [[Bert Glennon]]\n| editing        = Sherman Todd\n| studio         = Sol Lesser Productions \n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1940|05|24|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Our Town''''' is a 1940 American [[drama (genre)|drama]] [[romance film]] adaptation of a [[Our Town|play of the same name]] by [[Thornton Wilder]] starring  [[Martha Scott]] as Emily Webb, and [[William Holden]] as George Gibbs.  The cast also included [[Fay Bainter]], [[Beulah Bondi]], [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]], [[Guy Kibbee]]  and [[Frank Craven]].  It was adapted by [[Harry Chandlee]], Craven and Wilder, and directed by [[Sam Wood]].\n\nThe film was a faithful reproduction of the play except for two significant changes: the film used scenery, whereas the play had not; the events of the third act, which in the play revolve around the death of one of the main characters, were turned into a dream from which Emily awakens \u2014 she is then able to resume a normal life. Producer [[Sol Lesser]] worked with Wilder in creating these changes.\n\nA radio adaptation of the film on ''[[Lux Radio Theater]]'' on May 6, 1940, used the altered film ending.\n\nThe U.S. copyright of the film was not renewed after its first term expired in 1968. However, because it is a [[derivative work]] from a play that is still under U.S. copyright, it is not deemed to be in the [[public domain]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=24em}}\n* [[William Holden]] - George Gibbs\n* [[Martha Scott]] - Emily Webb\n* [[Fay Bainter]] - Mrs. Julia Gibbs\n* Dix Davis - Joe Crowell Jr.\n* [[Beulah Bondi]] - Mrs. Myrtle Webb\n* [[Thomas Mitchell (actor)|Thomas Mitchell]] - Dr. Frank F. Gibbs\n* [[Guy Kibbee]] - Mr. Charles Webb\n* Tim Davis - Si Crowell\n* [[Stuart Erwin]] - Howie Newsome\n* [[Frank Craven]] - Stage Manager\n* [[Doro Merande]] - Mrs. Louella Soames\n* Philip Wood - Simon Stimson\n* Ruth Tobey - Rebecca Gibbs (as Ruth Toby)\n* Douglas Gardiner - Wally Webb\n* Arthur B. Allen - Prof. Willard (as Arthur Allen)\n* [[Charles Trowbridge]] - Rev. Dr. Ferguson\n* [[Spencer Charters]] - Const. Bill Warren\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Score==\n[[Aaron Copland]] accepted the invitation to compose the musical score for the screen version of life in the small town of Grover's Corners, New Hampshire. He explained, \"For the film version, they were counting on the music to translate the transcendental aspects of the story. I tried for clean and clear sounds and in general used straight-forward harmonies and rhythms that would project the serenity and sense of security of the story.\" Copland arranged about ten minutes from the film score for a suite. It is dedicated to [[Leonard Bernstein]].<ref name=\"Boosey & Hawkes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boosey.com/cr/music/Aaron-Copland-Our-Town/2258 |title=Copland, Aaron Our Town (1940) Music from the film score |accessdate=2018-11-19|work=Boosey.com}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/36778/Our-Town/details |title=NY Times: Our Town |accessdate=2008-12-13|work=NY Times}}</ref>  Scott, who reprised her stage role as Emily Webb, was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. [[Aaron Copland]] was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]] and [[Thomas T. Moulton]] was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound]].<ref name=\"Oscars1941\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1941 |title=The 13th Academy Awards (1941) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-08-13|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title | id=0032881 | title=Our Town}}\n* {{amg movie|36778}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=85941}}\n* {{AFI film|id=4334|title=Our Town}}\n* {{Internet Archive film|id=Our_Town|name=Our Town}}\n\n{{Sam Wood}}\n{{Thornton Wilder}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Our Town (1940 Film)}}\n[[Category:1940 films]]\n[[Category:1940s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sam Wood]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Sol Lesser]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Aaron Copland]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1901]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1904]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1913]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\nhttps://variety.com/1939/film/reviews/our-town-1200413018/\n", "name_user": "Mucketymuck", "label": "safe", "comment": "Character's name hasn't been given here (and, come to that, need not be).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Our_Town_(1940_film)"}
{"title_page": "Frederick Lane", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian swimmer}}\n{{other people||Fred Lane (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Frederick Lane\n| image          = Fred Lane 1900.jpg\n| image_size     = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Lane at 1900 Olympics\n| fullname       = Frederick Claude Vivian Lane\n| nicknames      = \"Fred\", \"Freddie\"\n| national_team  = {{AUS}}\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]]\n| club           = Blackpool SC<br>East Sydney Amateur SC \n| coach          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1880|2|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Millers Point, New South Wales]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|1969|5|14|1880|2|2|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Avalon, New South Wales]]\n| height         = <!-- {{convert|x.xx|m|ftin|abbr=on}} -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|xx|kg|lb|abbr=on}} -->\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | Australia}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre obstacle event|200 m obstacle]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Claude Vivian Lane''' (2 February 1880 &ndash; 14 May 1969) was an Australian [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who competed at the [[1900 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Lane|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/la/fred-lane-1.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nLane, from [[Manly, New South Wales]], was four years old when his brother saved him from drowning in [[Sydney Harbour]], whereupon he decided to learn to swim. Later, he attended [[high school]] at [[Saint Ignatius' College, Riverview]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Lane, Frederick Claude Vivian (1879\u20131969)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/lane-frederick-claude-vivian-7023|website=adb.anu.edu.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter breaking many Australasian swimming records, Lane moved to [[England]] to compete in the English Championships in 1899.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nHe was the first Australian to represent his country in swimming at the [[Olympic Games]], when he competed at the [[1900 Summer Olympics]] in Paris, and won two gold medals. He first won the [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 metres freestyle]], clearly beating Hungarian [[Zolt\u00e1n Halmay]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming at the 1900 Paris Summer Games: Men's 200 metres Freestyle|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1900/SWI/mens-200-metres-freestyle.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> His second final was just 45 minutes later, the discontinued [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre obstacle event|200 metre obstacle event]], where he beat Austrian [[Otto Wahle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming at the 1900 Paris Summer Games: Men's 200 metres Obstacle Course|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1900/SWI/mens-200-metres-obstacle-course.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Lane stayed in England for another two years working for a legal firm in [[Blackpool]] while he continued to swim and break records. In July 1902, he won a 100 yard race and became the first person to record one minute dead for that distance.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In August, he swam 220 yards in 2 minutes 28.6 seconds, which in 1974 was ratified by [[FINA]] as the first World Record for 200 metres.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In October, he broke the one-minute barrier for 100 yards in 59.6 seconds.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn returning to Australia, Lane became a master printer and a partner in a printing and stationery firm on [[Bridge Street, Sydney]]. He married in 1908. He died in 1969 at [[Avalon, New South Wales]]. He was survived by a son and a daughter.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn 1969, Lane was honoured by the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]].<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=FREDERICK \"FREDDIE\" LANE (AUS) 1969 Honor Swimmer|url=http://www.ishof.org/frederick-freddie-lane-(aus).html|website=ISHOF.org|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 1985, Lane was inducted into the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fredrick 'Freddie' Lane - Swimming|url=https://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=396&memberType=athlete|website=sahof.org.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Manly sc.jpg |thumb|Lane, standing at right, with Manly Swimming Club teammates]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of members of the International Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n* [[World record progression 200 metres freestyle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://www.ishof.org/frederick-freddie-lane-(aus).html  Frederick \"Freddie\" Lane (AUS)] &ndash; Honor Swimmer profile at International Swimming Hall of Fame\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 200 m Freestyle Men}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lane, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Grammar School]]\n[[Category:World record setters in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian swimmer}}\n{{other people||Fred Lane (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Frederick Lane\n| image          = Fred Lane 1900.jpg\n| image_size     = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Lane at 1900 Olympics\n| fullname       = Frederick Claude Vivian Lane\n| nicknames      = \"Fred\", \"Freddie\"\n| national_team  = {{AUS}}\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]]\n| club           = Blackpool SC<br>East Sydney Amateur SC \n| coach          = \n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1880|2|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Millers Point, New South Wales]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|1969|5|14|1880|2|2|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Avalon, New South Wales]]\n| height         = <!-- {{convert|x.xx|m|ftin|abbr=on}} -->\n| weight         = <!-- {{convert|xx|kg|lb|abbr=on}} -->\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | Australia}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre obstacle event|200 m obstacle]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Claude Vivian Lane''' (2 February 1880 &ndash; 14 May 1969) was an Australian [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who competed at the [[1900 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Lane|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/la/fred-lane-1.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nLane, from [[Manly, New South Wales]], was four years old when his brother saved him from drowning in [[Sydney Harbour]], whereupon he decided to learn to swim. Later, he attended [[high school]] at [[Saint Ignatius' College, Riverview]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Lane, Frederick Claude Vivian (1879\u20131969)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/lane-frederick-claude-vivian-7023|website=adb.anu.edu.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter breaking many Australasian swimming records, Lane moved to [[England]] to compete in the English Championships in 1899.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nHe was the first Australian to represent his country in swimming at the [[Olympic Games]], when he competed at the [[1900 Summer Olympics]] in Paris, and won two gold medals. He first won the [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 metres freestyle]], clearly beating Hungarian [[Zolt\u00e1n Halmay]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming at the 1900 Paris Summer Games: Men's 200 metres Freestyle|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1900/SWI/mens-200-metres-freestyle.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> His second final was just 45 minutes later, the discontinued [[Swimming at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre obstacle event|200 metre obstacle event]], where he beat Austrian [[Otto Wahle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming at the 1900 Paris Summer Games: Men's 200 metres Obstacle Course|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1900/SWI/mens-200-metres-obstacle-course.html|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Lane stayed in England for another two years working for a legal firm in [[Blackpool]] while he continued to swim and break records. In July 1902, he won a 100 yard race and became the first person to record one minute dead for that distance.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In August, he swam 220 yards in 2 minutes 28.6 seconds, which in 1974 was ratified by [[FINA]] as the first World Record for 200 metres.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In October, he broke the one-minute barrier for 100 yards in 59.6 seconds.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn returning to Australia, Lane became a master printer and a partner in a printing and stationary firm on [[Bridge Street, Sydney]]. He married in 1908. He died in 1969 at [[Avalon, New South Wales]]. He was survived by a son and a daughter.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nIn 1969, Lane was honoured by the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]].<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=FREDERICK \"FREDDIE\" LANE (AUS) 1969 Honor Swimmer|url=http://www.ishof.org/frederick-freddie-lane-(aus).html|website=ISHOF.org|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 December 1985, Lane was inducted into the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fredrick 'Freddie' Lane - Swimming|url=https://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=396&memberType=athlete|website=sahof.org.au|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:Manly sc.jpg |thumb|Lane, standing at right, with Manly Swimming Club teammates]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of members of the International Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n* [[World record progression 200 metres freestyle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://www.ishof.org/frederick-freddie-lane-(aus).html  Frederick \"Freddie\" Lane (AUS)] &ndash; Honor Swimmer profile at International Swimming Hall of Fame\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 200 m Freestyle Men}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lane, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Grammar School]]\n[[Category:World record setters in swimming]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: stationary firm \u2192 stationery firm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_Lane"}
{"title_page": "Kelkheim", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|type              = Town\n|image_coa         = Kelkheim-Wappen.svg\n|image_photo       = Ehem. Franziskanerkloster Kelkheim (Taunus).JPG\n|image_caption     = Former [[Franciscan]] abbey upon the ''Klosterberg'' (''abbey hill'') in the east of Kelkheim.\n|coordinates       = {{coord|50|8|16|N|08|26|59|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan        = Kelkheim (Taunus) in MTK.svg\n|state             = Hessen\n|region            = Darmstadt\n|district          = Main-Taunus-Kreis\n|elevation         = 100-515\n|area              = 30.65\n|postal_code       = 65779\n|area_code         = 06195, 06198&nbsp;(Eppenhain), 06174&nbsp;(Ruppertshain)\n|licence           = MTK\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 06 4 36 008\n|divisions         = 6 [[Stadtteil]]e\n|website           = [https://www.kelkheim.de/ www.kelkheim.de]\n|mayor             = Albrecht K\u00fcndiger\n|party             = \n}}\n\n'''Kelkheim''' is a town in the [[Main-Taunus-Kreis|Main-Taunus]] district in [[Hesse]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Geography==\n===Location===\nLocated on the southwestern slopes of the [[Taunus]] mountains, Kelkheim is noted for its attractive scenery. Kelkheim is located approximately 10&nbsp;km to the west of [[Frankfurt]]. [[Wiesbaden]], the state capital of Hesse, is about 25&nbsp;km away, while the [[Mainz]], the state capital of [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], is about 30&nbsp;km away. \n\n==Town districts==\nKelkheim is subdivided into six [[boroughs]] Kelkheim-Mitte, M\u00fcnster, Hornau, [[Fischbach (Taunus)|Fischbach]], Ruppertshain and Eppenhain.\n\n==Town partnerships==\nKelkheim is twinned to the following towns:<ref>[https://www.kelkheim.de/_rubric/index.php?rubric=DE+Freizeit+Kultur+Partnerst%E4dte Website Kelkheim]</ref>\n*{{flagicon|UK}} [[High Wycombe]], [[United Kingdom]] since 1985\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Saint-Fons|Saint Fons]], [[France]] since 1971\n\n==Public transportation==\n[[Kelkheim station]] is connected to both [[Frankfurt]] and [[K\u00f6nigstein im Taunus|K\u00f6nigstein]] by rail, while bus connections exist to [[Eppstein]], [[K\u00f6nigstein im Taunus|K\u00f6nigstein]], [[Liederbach am Taunus|Liederbach]] and [[Sulzbach, Hesse|Sulzbach]]. [[Frankfurt Airport]] serves as the city's main international airport and is located near to Kelkheim.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kelkheim (Taunus)}}\n{{Wiktionary|Kelkheim}}\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|de}}\n* {{HessBib PPN|116346868}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4030179-5}}\n\n{{Towns and municipalities in Main-Taunus-Kreis district}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Main-Taunus-Kreis]]\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|type              = Town\n|image_coa         = Kelkheim-Wappen.svg\n|image_photo       = Ehem. Franziskanerkloster Kelkheim (Taunus).JPG|thumb\n|image_caption     = Former [[Franciscan]] abbey upon the ''Klosterberg'' (''abbey hill'') in the east of Kelkheim.\n|coordinates       = {{coord|50|8|16|N|08|26|59|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan        = Kelkheim (Taunus) in MTK.svg\n|state             = Hessen\n|region            = Darmstadt\n|district          = Main-Taunus-Kreis\n|elevation         = 100-515\n|area              = 30.65\n|postal_code       = 65779\n|area_code         = 06195, 06198&nbsp;(Eppenhain), 06174&nbsp;(Ruppertshain)\n|licence           = MTK\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 06 4 36 008\n|LOCODE            = DE KHM\n|divisions         = 6 [[Stadtteil]]e\n|Stra\u00dfe            = Gagernring 6\n|website           = [https://www.kelkheim.de/ www.kelkheim.de]\n|mayor             = Albrecht K\u00fcndiger\n|party             = \n}}\n\n'''Kelkheim''' is a town in the [[Main-Taunus-Kreis|Main-Taunus]] district in [[Hesse]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Geography==\n===Location===\nLocated on the southwestern slopes of the [[Taunus]] mountains, Kelkheim is noted for its attractive scenery. Kelkheim is located approximately 10&nbsp;km to the west of [[Frankfurt]]. [[Wiesbaden]], the state capital of Hesse, is about 25&nbsp;km away, while the [[Mainz]], the state capital of [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], is about 30&nbsp;km away. \n\n==Town districts==\nKelkheim is subdivided into six [[boroughs]] Kelkheim-Mitte, M\u00fcnster, Hornau, [[Fischbach (Taunus)|Fischbach]], Ruppertshain and Eppenhain.\n\n==Town partnerships==\nKelkheim is twinned to the following towns:<ref>[https://www.kelkheim.de/_rubric/index.php?rubric=DE+Freizeit+Kultur+Partnerst%E4dte Website Kelkheim]</ref>\n*{{flagicon|UK}} [[High Wycombe]], [[United Kingdom]] since 1985\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Saint-Fons|Saint Fons]], [[France]] since 1971\n\n==Public transportation==\n[[Kelkheim station]] is connected to both [[Frankfurt]] and [[K\u00f6nigstein im Taunus|K\u00f6nigstein]] by rail, while bus connections exist to [[Eppstein]], [[K\u00f6nigstein im Taunus|K\u00f6nigstein]], [[Liederbach am Taunus|Liederbach]] and [[Sulzbach, Hesse|Sulzbach]]. [[Frankfurt Airport]] serves as the city's main international airport and is located near to Kelkheim.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kelkheim (Taunus)}}\n{{Wiktionary|Kelkheim}}\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|de}}\n* {{HessBib PPN|116346868}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|4030179-5}}\n\n{{Towns and municipalities in Main-Taunus-Kreis district}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Main-Taunus-Kreis]]\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelkheim"}
{"title_page": "South Park (season 23)", "text_new": "{{short description|Season of television series}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number = 23\n| bgcolour = #B9E1FA\n| image = File: Sps23bluray.jpg\n| caption = Blu-ray cover\n| country = United States\n| network = [[Comedy Central]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2019|12|11}}\n| num_episodes = 10<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| episode_list = [[List of South Park episodes|List of ''South Park'' episodes]]\n}}\nThe twenty-third season of the American [[animated sitcom]] series ''[[South Park]]'' premiered on [[Comedy Central]] on September 25, 2019, and concluded on December 11, 2019; after 10 episodes aired.<ref name=\"PremiereDate\">{{cite web |last1=Nissen |first1=Dano |title=TV News Roundup: Comedy Central Sets 'South Park' Season 23 Premiere Date |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-roundup-south-park-comedy-central-1203272467/ |website=Variety |date=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> This season contained the 300th episode of the long-running TV show; the milestone was reached on October 9, 2019, when the third episode of the season premiered. Like previous seasons, this season also had dark weeks (weeks during which no new episode would air), after episodes four and seven. [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] continued to write, direct, and edit every episode the week prior to air, as the duo has done since the series debuted in 1997.<ref name=\"thewrap\" />\n\nSimilar to previous seasons, the season features continuing elements and a recurring storyline, from episodes 1 through 6, without adhering to a linear story arc, while lampooning [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement#Detention centers|ICE detention centers]], the 2019 film ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'',  media [[censorship in China]], the [[antivaccine movement]], plant based food, the [[Trump Administration]], [[transgenderism]] in athletics, and the competition between traditional [[cable television]] and media streaming.\n\n==Production==\nOn July 8, 2015, two months prior to the season 19 premiere, Comedy Central announced they had renewed ''South Park'' for an additional 30 episodes over three seasons. This renewal was in addition to the two-year contract already in place with Parker and Stone, guaranteeing ''South Park'' would air until at least 2019.<ref name=\"thewrap\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/south-park-scores-3-season-renewal-set-to-top-300-episodes/|title='South Park' Renewed for 3 More Seasons|first=Tony|last=Maglio|website=[[The Wrap]]|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/south-park-renewed-three-seasons-2019-comedy-central-1201472071/|title='South Park' Renewed For Three More Seasons|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/south-park-renewed-2019-comedy-central-1201535909/|title='South Park' Renewed by Comedy Central Through 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2019|last=Steinberg|first=Brian}}</ref> On September 12, 2019, the show was renewed for seasons 24 through 26 until 2022.<ref>{{cite press release|title='South Park' Renewed Through Historic 26th Season|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/09/12/south-park-renewed-through-historic-26th-season-391304/20190912comedycentral01/|website=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Main theme==\n{{see also|South Park#Main theme}}\nThis season had multiple changes to the traditional [[theme song]] from the show. For the first six episodes of the season, an overall story arc focusing on [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|Randy Marsh]]'s marijuana farm named Tegridy Farms was featured. During these episodes, the theme song's lyrics and graphics were changed to focus on Tegridy Farms and also featured vocals by Randy Marsh and [[Towelie (character)|Towelie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QQN1l1_Mt7k|title=South Park Gets a New Theme Song Courtesy of Tegridy Farms|website=[[YouTube]]|date=September 26, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref> In the episode \"[[Board Girls]]\", the regular theme was completely abandoned and replaced with a theme about the PC Babies, the [[politically correct]] children of [[PC Principal]] and Vice Principal [[List of South Park Elementary staff#Strong Woman|Strong Woman]]. In the \"[[Turd Burglars]]\" episode, the theme returned to the show, but starring the women of South Park, in a fictional show titled \"One for the Ladies\". In the \"[[Basic Cable (South Park)|Basic Cable]]\" episode, the theme was abandoned again and replaced with a faux intro titled \"The Scott Malkinson Show\". The traditional theme song was put back in on the final episode \"[[Christmas Snow (South Park)|Christmas Snow]]\".\n\n==Controversy==\nOn October 7, 2019, ''South Park'' was reportedly banned from the Chinese Internet with videos, mentions, and discussion forums for the animated series being removed and shut down in response to episode 2 of the season, \"[[Band in China]]\". Later in the day ''South Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone mockingly apologized.<ref>{{cite web|title='South Park' creators issue a mocking 'apology' to China after the show was reportedly banned in the country|url=https://www.businessinsider.nl/south-park-creators-issue-mock-apology-to-china-after-ban-2019-10?international=true&r=US|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=October 7, 2019|last=Clark|first=Travis}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{see also|List of South Park episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table|background=#B9E1FA |overall=|season=|title=|titleR=|airdate=|airdateR=<ref name=\"futon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/south-park/listings/|title=Shows 